            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Michelle Bernstein\u2019s life has been a study in organized, flavorful chaos. The daughter of a pragmatic Chinese-American mother from San Francisco's Richmond District and a boisterous Jewish-American father from New York, Michelle grew up in Daly City where the family kitchen was a constant fusion of sizzling ginger and simmering brisket. Food was their love language, and from a young age, Michelle learned that the best meals weren\u2019t about extravagance, but about intention and welcome. This foundation naturally led her to pursue a Hospitality Management degree at San Francisco State University.\n\nHer career began not with a bang, but with the steady grind of a true restaurant lifer. She was a hostess, a server, a barback, and eventually, a sharp-eyed general manager at a popular Hayes Valley bistro. Her turning point came eight years ago when the Farmstead Restaurant Group acquired the struggling bistro. While most of the old management was let go, the new owners saw a spark in Michelle\u2019s unflappable competence. She was promoted and tasked with stabilizing operations. By focusing on staff morale and streamlining supply chains, she transformed the location into one of the group\u2019s most profitable, earning her a swift ascent to Director of Operations.\n\nNow 42, Michelle\u2019s life is a meticulously scheduled ballet. Her mornings begin before sunrise in her cozy Inner Richmond apartment, followed by a 5.8-mile MUNI ride downtown, a quiet ritual of scanning emails and mentally preparing for the day. Her work is a whirlwind of spreadsheets, vendor negotiations, and site visits to Farmstead\u2019s various locations. A long-term relationship ended five years ago, a casualty of her demanding schedule, and her social life now revolves around a close-knit circle of chefs and industry veterans.\n\nMichelle is deeply connected to San Francisco, not just as a resident but as a curator of its dining experiences. She feels the city\u2019s pulse through its produce markets and the hum of its kitchens. Though proud of her corporate success, her true dream is quieter. She hopes to one day leave the operations world behind and open her own small, 30-seat neighborhood restaurant\u2014a place that feels like her childhood kitchen, built on intention, welcome, and the simple joy of a perfectly executed meal."
